ion, DeploymentUmbrella: Risk Management, QA, Configuration Management, Technical Reviews\n\nTask Sets & Work ProductsTask Set includes:Work tasksWork productsQuality assurance pointsProject milestonesTailored for each action (e.g., elicitation, design, coding)\n\nWork Product ExamplesSource CodeDesign DocumentsRequirement SpecsTest CasesUser Manuals\n\nUnderstanding Process FlowsLinearIterativeEvolutionaryParallel\n\nProcess Flow\nSequential steps: Communication  Planning  Modeling  Construction  DeploymentSuitable for: Stable, well-understood projects\nProcess Flow\nIterative Flow: Repeat certain activities as needed before proceeding.Good for: Projects with evolving understanding\nProcess Flow\nProgressively build more complete versions in cycles.Used when: Requirements are vague or dynamic\nProcess Flow\nDifferent components handled in parallel.Good for: multi-team, modular projects\nDening AcEviEes in PracEceActivities need to be adapted to:Project complexityTeam size and skillStakeholder involvement\n\nExample: Communication ActivityFor small project:Call stakeholderNote requirementsSend summary for reviewFor large project:Inception, Elicitation, Elaboration, etc.\n\n\nTask Set: Small vs. Large ProjectSmall: stakeholder meeting list featuresfinalizeLarge: multiple interviewsscenario analysis\n\nAssessing the ProcessUse metrics to assess progressAnalyze quality, timeliness, risksContinuous process improvement needed\n\nPrescripEve Models OverviewPredefined structure and order:WaterfallPrototypingSpiralUnified ProcessEach has defined flows, activities, tasks\nWaterfall ModelLinear sequence of phasesPros: Simple Clear stagesCons: Rigid Late testing Assumes clear requirements\n\nReal projects rarely follow the sequential work flow that the model proposes.It is often difficult for the customer to state all requirements explicitly at the beginning of most projects.The customer must have patience because a working version of the program(s) will not be available until