], "suggested_length": "4 paragraphs"}]	["A software process is a framework of activities, actions, and tasks to build high-quality software, the five framework activities are Communication, Planning, Modeling, Construction, and Deployment. Umbrella activities such as Risk Management, QA, Configuration Management, and Technical Reviews support the framework activities.\\r\\n\\r\\nThis process provides systematic guidance throughout the software life cycle, from requirements gathering to post-release maintenance. Without a good process, software projects tend to be undirected, error-prone, and difficult to control, especially in terms of quality, time, and cost. \\r\\n\\r\\nThe five main activities in the software process framework are Communication, Planning, Modeling, Construction, and Deployment. Communication plays a role in ensuring that user needs and expectations are clearly understood by the development team. Planning helps in establishing estimates of time, resources, and scheduling of the project. Modeling involves representing software requirements and designs visually or descriptively to ensure proper architecture and functionality. Construction involves coding and testing the software, while Deployment is the process of delivering the software to users and receiving feedback for improvement.\\r\\n\\r\\nUmbrella activities such as Risk Management, Quality Assurance, Configuration Management, and Technical Review are essential in supporting the five framework activities. For example, risk management helps identify and mitigate obstacles before they become major problems. Quality assurance ensures that each stage of development follows certain standards to maintain product quality. Configuration management ensures consistency between software versions during development, while technical review helps detect errors early. These umbrella activities run in parallel and continuously throughout the development process, ensuring that the end result is software that is reliable, secure, and meets user needs.", "Waterfall model: Linear sequence of phases; simple, clear stages but rigid and assumes clear requirements., Prototyping model: Build prototype quickly for feedback; fast validation, user involvement but risk of scope creep and quality compromise., Waterfall suitable for stable, well-understood projects. Prototyping suitable for customer-facing apps with vague specs, UI/UX testing.\\r\\nThe main advantage of the Waterfall model is its simplicity and clarity of structure. Each phase has a clear and well-documented purpose, making it easy to control and monitor. This model is suitable for projects with clearly defined requirements from the start and rarely changing. However, its disadvantage is its rigid nature and inflexibility to change. If something goes wrong in the early stages, it will be difficult to fix it in later stages because there is no mechanism for quick feedback or revision.\\r\\n\\r\\nWaterfall model follows a linear approach where each phase such as requirements analysis, design, implementation, testing, and maintenance is completed sequentially. In contrast, the Prototyping model is iterative, where an initial prototype of the system is built quickly to obtain user feedback, and then refined gradually until it meets the requirements.\\r\\n\\r\\nThe main advantage of the Waterfall model is its simplicity and clarity of structure. Each phase has a clear and well-documented purpose, making it easy to control and monitor. This model is suitable for projects with clearly defined requirements from the start and rarely changing. However, its disadvantage is its rigid nature and inflexibility to change. If something goes wrong in the early stages, it will be difficult to correct it in the later stages because there is no mechanism for quick feedback or revision.\\r\\n\\r\\nThe Prototyping model has the advantage of user involvement and the ability to validate needs early on. By building prototypes quickly, users can see and try the system early, and provide feedback that can be used immediately for improvements. This model is very effective in projects with unclear requirements, or those that rely heavily on the user interface (UI/UX). However, this model also has disadvantages, such as the risk of constantly changing requirements (scope creep), time and cost overruns, and prototypes that are sometimes not developed with good code quality. \\r\\n\\r\\nThe Waterfall model is best suited for projects with a stable scope, such as internal financial systems or software for highly regulated industries. On the other hand, the Prototyping model is better suited for applications that directly interact with end users, such as mobile applications, e-commerce systems, or web-based software, where the user experience and needs are not fully understood are the main focus. Choosing the right model is critical to ensuring development efficiency and project success.", "Process flows in software engineering describe the flow or sequence of activities in the software development process. Choosing the right type of process flow is critical because it affects how the team works, how requirements are gathered and translated, and the speed and quality of product delivery. Four commonly used types of process flows are linear flow, iterative flow, evolutionary flow, and parallel flow, each of which is suited to different project characteristics.\\r\\n\\r\\nLinear flow is an approach that follows sequential steps, where each phase (such as requirements analysis, design, implementation, testing, and maintenance) is completed one by one without going back to the previous stage. This model is suitable for stable, well-understood projects where the requirements and scope are clear from the start, such as financial reporting systems or internal banking applications. The advantage is that the workflow is structured and easy to monitor, but it is less flexible in dealing with changing requirements midway.\\r\\n\\r\\nIterative flow allows teams to repeat certain activities as needed, such as design and testing, so that the system can be refined based on the learnings from each cycle. This model is good for projects with evolving understanding, such as educational applications or e-learning systems that require incremental refinement based on user feedback. Iterations provide flexibility and the opportunity to avoid major mistakes early on.\\r\\n\\r\\nMeanwhile, evolutionary flow allows teams to progressively build more complete versions in cycles, which is especially useful when requirements are vague or dynamic. For example, in the development of a new social media application, core features can be built first, then further developed based on feedback from early users. On the other hand, parallel flow allows different components to be handled in parallel, which is good for multi-team, modular projects. An example is a large ERP system, where the finance, HR, and inventory modules are developed by different teams simultaneously. This approach speeds up development but requires good coordination and integration across teams."]	70	[{"question_index": 0, "score": 70, "feedback": "Answer received. Consider providing more detailed analysis based on course materials.", "user_answer": "A software process is a framework of activities, actions, and tasks to build high-quality software, the five framework activities are Communication, Planning, Modeling, Construction, and Deployment. Umbrella activities such as Risk Management, QA, Configuration Management, and Technical Reviews support the framework activities.\\r\\n\\r\\nThis process provides systematic guidance throughout the software life cycle, from requirements gathering to post-release maintenance. Without a good process, software projects tend to be undirected, error-prone, and difficult to control, especially in terms of quality, time, and cost. \\r\\n\\r\\nThe five main activities in the software process framework 